hemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"glm-5.2[1m]":{"inputTokens":15087,"outputTokens":10065,"cacheReadInputTokens":5248,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.32968400000000003,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"The Phase 9A stranding follow-up broadens three exception handlers in `cross_run_queue_run_once()` (harness/cli.py): (1) the `try_claim_job` claim path, (2) the `load_job_payload` load path, both changed from `except HarnessCliError` to `except Exception`, and (3) a new outer `except Exception` around the execution body that marks the queue entry terminal-failed, reports it skipped, and sets the flag so the shared `finally` releases the queue claim lock. Two of the three changes are directly covered by new regression tests asserting the entry is `failed` and `entries/entry-a/claim.lock` is absent (load path via `OSError`, execution path via `RuntimeError`). The claim-path change (try_claim_job raising) is NOT directly exercised by any test: the only relevant test patches `try_claim_job` with `return_value=None` (no exception) and injects the failure via `load_job_payload` instead. This leaves a gap in coverage for a stranding scenario explicitly listed as a fixed area. I relied on the provided verification summary for pass/fail results since tests could not be executed in this read-only review.","findings":[{"severity":"medium","title":"Claim-path (try_claim_job) non-HarnessCliError exception handling lacks direct regression coverage","evidence":"The diff changes the claim-path handler from `except HarnessCliError as exc:` to `except Exception as exc:` immediately after the `try_claim_job(...)` call (harness/cli.py ~line 2554). The verification summary lists the claim path as a fixed area ('handles non-HarnessCliError exceptions from referenced-job claim and load paths'). However, the new test `test_cross_run_queue_run_once_marks_unloadable_referenced_job_failed_without_stranding_lock` patches `cli.try_claim_job` with `return_value=None` (no exception raised) and injects the failure via `mock.patch.object(cli, \"load_job_payload\", side_effect=OSError(\"disk unavailable\"))`. No test patches `try_claim_job` with a `side_effect` raising a non-HarnessCliError, so the claim-path except block's behavior (marking the entry terminal and releasing the queue claim lock via the shared `finally`) is not directly verified. Because `try_claim_job` performs filesystem claim operations where OSError/PermissionError is plausible, and a stranded queue `claim.lock` blocks the entry permanently, this is an untested stranding scenario.","recommendation":"Add a regression test that patches `cli.try_claim_job` with `side_effect=OSError(\"claim io failure\")` (and does NOT patch `load_job_payload`), then asserts `summary[\"executed_entries\"] == []`, `summary[\"skipped_entries\"] == [\"entry-a\"]`, `entry[\"status\"] == \"failed\"`, `entry[\"terminal_job_status\"] is None`, and that `entries/entry-a/claim.lock` does not exist.","file":"harness/cli.py","line":2554}],"tested":["Load-path change: `load_job_payload` raising `OSError` marks entry `failed`, reports `skipped_entries=[\"entry-a\"]`, and leaves no `claim.lock` (test present).","Execution-path change: new outer `except Exception` catches `RuntimeError` from `execute_claimed_generic_agent_job`, marks entry `failed`, reports skipped, and releases the queue claim lock so `claim.lock` is absent (test present).","Both new regression tests assert the queue entry's `status == \"failed\"`, `terminal_job_status is None`, and that `entries/entry-a/claim.lock` does not exist (direct stranding check).","Static-structure check: claim/load except blocks are nested at 12-space indent inside the outer 8-space try/except/finally that performs `release_cross_run_queue_claim`, confirming claim/load handlers share the same release path as the outer handler.","Relying on provided verification summary: `tests.test_cross_run_queue` -> 19 OK, static contracts -> 18 OK / 1 skipped, `git diff --check` exit 0."],"not_tested":["Direct injection of a non-HarnessCliError exception from `try_claim_job` to confirm the claim-path except block (line ~2554) marks terminal and releases the lock; the existing test only sets `return_value=None` and fails via `load_job_payload`.","Full bodies of the claim-path and load-path except blocks are not visible in the diff (only the `except` line changed); the claim-path body's exact statements (e.g., whether it `continue`s) were inferred from indentation/structure, not confirmed from source.","`mark_cross_run_queue_entry_terminal`'s own failure behavior is not covered; if writing `entry.json` raises (e.g., disk full), behavior is undefined by these tests.","Tests were not re-run in this read-only review; pass counts are taken from the supplied verification summary."],"residual_risks":["Latent stranding if `mark_cross_run_queue_entry_terminal` itself raises inside any except block (e.g., disk full writing entry.json): `release_queue_claim` may never be set True, so the `finally` would not call `release_cross_run_queue_claim`, stranding the claim. This fragility affects the new outer `except Exception` and the pre-existing claim/load handlers equally. Consider releasing the claim unconditionally in `finally` (or before/around the mark-terminal call) rather than gating it on the flag.","Broad `except Exception` will also mask genuine programming errors (AttributeError, KeyError, TypeError from worker bugs) as a terminal-failed entry; the recorded reason string mitigates debugging but reduces error signal. Acceptable for preventing stranding, but worker-code bugs could be misclassified as transient job failures.","If `try_claim_job` returns None and code falls through to `load_job_payload` (as the test implies), the claim/load ordering should be re-confirmed against the full function body; 